<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-7846] A trait that defines a static method that uses generic return types throws &quot;BUG! Type is null&quot;</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-7846</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;If you have a trait that defines a method such as:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;    &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;static&lt;/span&gt; &amp;lt;T&amp;gt; T withClient(MyTrait myTrait, @DelegatesTo(MyTrait) Closure&amp;lt;T&amp;gt; callable ) {
        &lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// no-op
&lt;/span&gt;    }
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Compilation will fail with:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;BUG! Type is &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;null&lt;/span&gt;. Most probably you let a transform reuse existing ClassNodes with generics information, that is now used in a wrong context.
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
